Preliminary Analysis of the OPTN/UNOS Data

Fan Wu

April 22, 2016

Contents

Dates in the UNOS Datasets

There are several dates related to the transplant candidate/recipients defined in the waiting list dataset and the post-transplant follow-up dataset (the ones used to defind the event of interest are in bold).

  • DIALYSIS_DATE: WL date of initiation of regularly administered dialysis for ESRD (WL);
  • ACTIVATE_DATE: date when qualifying criteria were first entered (WL);
  • INIT_DATE: date placed on the waiting list (WL);
  • ADMISSION_DATE: recipient date of admission to the TX ctr (TRR);
  • TX_DATE: transplant date (TRR);
  • DEATH_DATE: date died for patients removed from the WL for reason of death (WL);
  • COMPOSITE_DEATH_DATE: composite patient death date from OPTN/external sources (TRR/TRF-Calc);
  • END_DATE: earliest date of removal from the WL (TX, D, or EOS) (WL);
  • FAIL_DATE_KI: graft fail date - kidney (TRR/TRF-Calc);
  • GRF_FAIL_DATE: date of graft failure (KIF);
  • PX_STAT_DATE: recipient status date at time of FU (KIF).

TOC

Brief Summary of the Data

We subset from the OPTN/UNOS data (as of Sept. 2015) the cohort used for one-year graft/patient survival analysis (Jul. 2012 – Dec. 2014) as reported on the SRTR website. There are in total 40297 ESRD patients (out of which 101 had more than one transplants) and 40398 kidney transplants from 229 transplant centers included in the analysis. For convenience, in this prelminary analysis, multiple transplants from the same patients are treated as indepenent observations. Below is a plot showing the center size (in number of TXs), and where the MIUM is (centers with size \(\geqslant\) 200 are plotted).

TOC

Diabetes Types as a Risk Factor

The DIAB in the data are coded as follows:

  • 1: No diabetes;
  • 2: Type I diabetes;
  • 3: Type II diabetes;
  • 4: Unknown, Missing, Not Reported.

Within those centers with size \(\geqslant\) 200, we also plot the % of diabetic patients (DIAB = 2, 3, 4) at TX.

We first check cross table for diabetes types with one-year graft failure, one-year mortality, mean recipient age and % of PVD.

To check the effect of diabetes types on the graft failure rate and mortality rate by the time period after TX (3 mo, 3-6 mo, 6-12 mo).

We then fit a stratified Cox model including all the risk factor listed as in our plan and using TX centers as the strata factor:

  • Recipient: Age, race, sex, BMI, sensitization status (using cPRA), diabetes, peripheral vascular disease,
  • Donor: Age, race, sex, BMI
  • Transplantation: cold ischemia time, HLA mismatch ( 0-2,3-4, 5-6), type of organ (living versus deceased)

Separate models are fitted for graft (T.GRF) and patient (T.PT).

The Wald-type test for testing \(H_0: \beta_{diab1} = \beta_{diab2}\) has p-value < 0.001 and < 0.001 for the Cox model for graft and patient survival, respectively. TOC

Interaction between Time on Dialysis and Diabetes

We first check the cross table between diabetes types and the dialysis time (pre-emptive: no dialysis recorded; 0-2 years, 2-4 years and 4 years+). The density plot of the exact time on dialysis is also plotted.

Then we inspect the one-year graft failure rate and the mortality rate for different combination of dialysis time and diabetes types.

As in last section, we also fit an all-in stratified Cox model with everything including the interaction between diabetes types and dialysis time. No interaction seems to be significant from the results, which kind of reflect the EDA finding in the plots/tables.
